# Frontend Design Skill

Use this rule whenever creating or updating frontend UI (HEEx, CSS, JS/TS). The goal is to produce distinctive, production-grade interfaces with a bold, intentional aesthetic and zero generic AI look.

## Design Approach

- Pick a clear purpose and audience; commit to a memorable visual direction (minimal, luxury, playful, brutalist, retro-futuristic, etc.). Every screen should have a differentiating idea someone will remember.
- Decide an explicit tone before coding and keep it cohesive (color, typography, motion, spacing).
- Avoid generic aesthetics (no default system fonts or tired purple gradients). Never ship something that looks templated or interchangeable.

## Typography

- Choose characterful fonts; pair a distinctive display font with a refined body font. Avoid generic families like Arial/Roboto/Inter.
- Use scale and weight intentionally; reserve display fonts for headlines and keep body text highly readable.

## Color & Atmosphere

- Build a tight palette with dominant hues and sharp accents; define CSS variables for consistency.
- Use backgrounds that add depth (gradients, grain, meshes, patterns) instead of flat whites when appropriate for the chosen aesthetic.

## Motion & Micro-interactions

- Prefer purposeful, high-impact moments (page load reveals, staggered transitions) over scattered animations.
- Use CSS-first motion when possible; ensure states have smooth hover/focus/active feedback.

## Layout & Composition

- Embrace intentional composition: asymmetry, layering, generous negative space or deliberate density—aligned with the chosen tone.
- Balance spacing and hierarchy; ensure key elements have breathing room and clear visual priority.

## Craft & Polish

- Add thoughtful details: refined shadows, borders, gradients, and hover states that reinforce the aesthetic.
- Keep interactions accessible (focus states, contrast) while staying on-brand.

## Delivery Expectations

- Ship working, production-ready code (HEEx/CSS/JS) with cohesive styling and animations that match the selected direction.
- Each implementation must feel bespoke to the context, not generic. If the design feels interchangeable, revisit typography, palette, and composition until it stands out.
